Europe needs an immigration restart
Brussels — Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for a safe port where their passengers can land.
Refugee and migrant camps on Lesbos Island in Greece are overflowing, and the conditions in other Libyan reception camps are similar.
Turkey has撕毁 the 2016 agreement that prevented migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help migrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015–16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged — many of them fleeing the Syrian conflict — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded governments' confidence in managing the EU's external borders and asylum systems, and also highlighted the failure of cooperation with migrant-sending countries.
Therefore, immigration has become a political football, a favorite issue for populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control over immigration while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to revise its policies in four areas and mobilize member states to take action for the benefit of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for maintaining open internal borders.
Any country in which people can move freely internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource external border control to a single state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, as well as a national task.
Frontex, the EU's Border and Coast Guard Agency, must be further strengthened and should deploy joint border guards with member states — including along coastlines and at airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Merging them has led the asylum system to the brink of collapse; handling them separately helps ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns with their rights protected.
Addressing the EU's real economic and social needs requires effective blue or green card policies for economic migrants and the implementation of overall immigration targets.
This cannot wait for the next immigration crisis to introduce these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, the policy must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer the question of what kind of EU support is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be addressed to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage immigration from outside the EU on their own.
However, reaching an agreement among governments on an overall EU immigration target would be a major step forward.
In return, member states could specify the source countries and specific criteria for the economic migrants they want, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept migrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting migrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skills, and age group.
Europe could also do this.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement for the compulsory distribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement has damaged the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if border, asylum, and immigration systems are sufficiently effective.
Furthermore, the frontline member states of the EU cannot be expected to solve the problem of illegal immigration crossing external borders alone.
The reception centers are overcrowded, and immigrants are subjected to abuse by authorities or driven north.
The responsibility of the first member state that the immigrants arrive in must be supplemented by EU cohesion.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to improve the actions and management capabilities of national asylum authorities.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected across the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of cross-border travel zones.
After improving the actions and management capabilities of national asylum authorities, the processing procedures for asylum applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with source and transit countries.
To facilitate the return of unauthorized migrants to their countries of origin, these connections are crucial.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
EU migration objectives, as well as skills cooperation to prepare for jobs in Europe, can be provided to third countries that seek stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes population explosions in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and shortages of job opportunities.
EU aid should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area could make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has an opportunity to move the EU away from instinctive reactions to migration crises toward a more coherent and sustained approach, whether internally or externally.
We must never miss this opportunity.
